"1383":"1383","1382":"1382","about 1374":"omkring 1374","about 1342":"omkring 1342","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Laxfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Laxfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1342–":"circa 1342–Overleden","1340–1383":"1340–1383","1358–1383":"1358–1383","1342–Female":"1342–Overleden","April 1358":"april 1358","1358":"1358","1455":"1455","1342":"1342","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","about 1374":"circa 1374","about 1342":"circa 1342","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Laxfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Laxfield, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1342–":"about 1342–Deceased","1340–1383":"1340–1383","1358–1383":"1358–1383","1342–Female":"1342–Deceased","April 1358":"April 1358","1358":"1358","1455":"1455","1342":"1342","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","about 1374":"about 1374","about 1342":"about 1342","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Laxfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Laxfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fiske","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from a farm in western Norway, named from Old Norse <i>fiskr</i> ‘fish’ + <i>-e</i> from <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’.","English (East Anglia): variant of   Fisk  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fisk","meanings":["English (East Anglia): metonymic occupational name for a fisherman or fish seller, or a nickname for someone supposedly resembling a fish in some way, from Old Norse <i>fiskr</i> ‘fish’ (cognate with Old English <i>fisc</i>). See   Fish   1."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":40,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":113,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Hugh Fiske was born about 1342, in Suffolk, England. She married Hugh Daniel Fiske about 1374. They wer